\title{Scikit Learn}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Machine learning in Python with scikit-learn. Use when working with supervised learning (classification, regression), unsupervised learning (clustering, dimensionality reduction), model evaluation, hyperparameter tuning, preprocessing, or building ML pipelines. Provides comprehensive reference documentation for algorithms, preprocessing techniques, pipelines, and best practices.}

\subtree{
\title{Scikit-learn}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{This skill provides comprehensive guidance for machine learning tasks using scikit-learn, the industry-standard Python library for classical machine learning. Use this skill for classification, regression, clustering, dimensionality reduction, preprocessing, model evaluation, and building production-ready ML pipelines.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Installation}
\pre{\startverb
# Install scikit-learn using uv
uv uv pip install scikit-learn

# Optional: Install visualization dependencies
uv uv pip install matplotlib seaborn

# Commonly used with
uv uv pip install pandas numpy
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{Use the scikit-learn skill when:}

\ul{
\li{Building classification or regression models}
\li{Performing clustering or dimensionality reduction}
\li{Preprocessing and transforming data for machine learning}
\li{Evaluating model performance with cross-validation}
\li{Tuning hyperparameters with grid or random search}
\li{Creating ML pipelines for production workflows}
\li{Comparing different algorithms for a task}
\li{Working with both structured (tabular) and text data}
\li{Need interpretable, classical machine learning approaches}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\subtree{
\title{Classification Example}
\pre{\startverb
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42
)

# Preprocess
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Train model
model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

# Evaluate
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Complete Pipeline with Mixed Data}
\pre{\startverb
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier

# Define feature types
numeric_features = ['age', 'income']
categorical_features = ['gender', 'occupation']

# Create preprocessing pipelines
numeric_transformer = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())
])

categorical_transformer = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('onehot', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))
])

# Combine transformers
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer([
    ('num', numeric_transformer, numeric_features),
    ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
])

# Full pipeline
model = Pipeline([
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('classifier', GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42))
])

# Fit and predict
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Capabilities}
\subtree{
\title{1. Supervised Learning}
\p{Comprehensive algorithms for classification and regression tasks.}

\p{\strong{Key algorithms:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Linear models}: Logistic Regression, Linear Regression, Ridge, Lasso, ElasticNet}
\li{\strong{Tree-based}: Decision Trees, Random Forest, Gradient Boosting}
\li{\strong{Support Vector Machines}: SVC, SVR with various kernels}
\li{\strong{Ensemble methods}: AdaBoost, Voting, Stacking}
\li{\strong{Neural Networks}: MLPClassifier, MLPRegressor}
\li{\strong{Others}: Naive Bayes, K-Nearest Neighbors}
}

\p{\strong{When to use:}}

\ul{
\li{Classification: Predicting discrete categories (spam detection, image classification, fraud detection)}
\li{Regression: Predicting continuous values (price prediction, demand forecasting)}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/supervised_learning.md\stopverb} for detailed algorithm documentation, parameters, and usage examples.}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Unsupervised Learning}
\p{Discover patterns in unlabeled data through clustering and dimensionality reduction.}

\p{\strong{Clustering algorithms:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Partition-based}: K-Means, MiniBatchKMeans}
\li{\strong{Density-based}: DBSCAN, HDBSCAN, OPTICS}
\li{\strong{Hierarchical}: AgglomerativeClustering}
\li{\strong{Probabilistic}: Gaussian Mixture Models}
\li{\strong{Others}: MeanShift, SpectralClustering, BIRCH}
}

\p{\strong{Dimensionality reduction:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Linear}: PCA, TruncatedSVD, NMF}
\li{\strong{Manifold learning}: t-SNE, UMAP, Isomap, LLE}
\li{\strong{Feature extraction}: FastICA, LatentDirichletAllocation}
}

\p{\strong{When to use:}}

\ul{
\li{Customer segmentation, anomaly detection, data visualization}
\li{Reducing feature dimensions, exploratory data analysis}
\li{Topic modeling, image compression}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/unsupervised_learning.md\stopverb} for detailed documentation.}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Model Evaluation and Selection}
\p{Tools for robust model evaluation, cross-validation, and hyperparameter tuning.}

\p{\strong{Cross-validation strategies:}}

\ul{
\li{KFold, StratifiedKFold (classification)}
\li{TimeSeriesSplit (temporal data)}
\li{GroupKFold (grouped samples)}
}

\p{\strong{Hyperparameter tuning:}}

\ul{
\li{GridSearchCV (exhaustive search)}
\li{RandomizedSearchCV (random sampling)}
\li{HalvingGridSearchCV (successive halving)}
}

\p{\strong{Metrics:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Classification}: accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, ROC AUC, confusion matrix}
\li{\strong{Regression}: MSE, RMSE, MAE, R², MAPE}
\li{\strong{Clustering}: silhouette score, Calinski-Harabasz, Davies-Bouldin}
}

\p{\strong{When to use:}}

\ul{
\li{Comparing model performance objectively}
\li{Finding optimal hyperparameters}
\li{Preventing overfitting through cross-validation}
\li{Understanding model behavior with learning curves}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/model_evaluation.md\stopverb} for comprehensive metrics and tuning strategies.}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Data Preprocessing}
\p{Transform raw data into formats suitable for machine learning.}

\p{\strong{Scaling and normalization:}}

\ul{
\li{StandardScaler (zero mean, unit variance)}
\li{MinMaxScaler (bounded range)}
\li{RobustScaler (robust to outliers)}
\li{Normalizer (sample-wise normalization)}
}

\p{\strong{Encoding categorical variables:}}

\ul{
\li{OneHotEncoder (nominal categories)}
\li{OrdinalEncoder (ordered categories)}
\li{LabelEncoder (target encoding)}
}

\p{\strong{Handling missing values:}}

\ul{
\li{SimpleImputer (mean, median, most frequent)}
\li{KNNImputer (k-nearest neighbors)}
\li{IterativeImputer (multivariate imputation)}
}

\p{\strong{Feature engineering:}}

\ul{
\li{PolynomialFeatures (interaction terms)}
\li{KBinsDiscretizer (binning)}
\li{Feature selection (RFE, SelectKBest, SelectFromModel)}
}

\p{\strong{When to use:}}

\ul{
\li{Before training any algorithm that requires scaled features (SVM, KNN, Neural Networks)}
\li{Converting categorical variables to numeric format}
\li{Handling missing data systematically}
\li{Creating non-linear features for linear models}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/preprocessing.md\stopverb} for detailed preprocessing techniques.}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. Pipelines and Composition}
\p{Build reproducible, production-ready ML workflows.}

\p{\strong{Key components:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Pipeline}: Chain transformers and estimators sequentially}
\li{\strong{ColumnTransformer}: Apply different preprocessing to different columns}
\li{\strong{FeatureUnion}: Combine multiple transformers in parallel}
\li{\strong{TransformedTargetRegressor}: Transform target variable}
}

\p{\strong{Benefits:}}

\ul{
\li{Prevents data leakage in cross-validation}
\li{Simplifies code and improves maintainability}
\li{Enables joint hyperparameter tuning}
\li{Ensures consistency between training and prediction}
}

\p{\strong{When to use:}}

\ul{
\li{Always use Pipelines for production workflows}
\li{When mixing numerical and categorical features (use ColumnTransformer)}
\li{When performing cross-validation with preprocessing steps}
\li{When hyperparameter tuning includes preprocessing parameters}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/pipelines_and_composition.md\stopverb} for comprehensive pipeline patterns.}
}
}

